import sys
!{sys.executable} -m pip install thinkx

import thinkdsp as tdsp
Analyzing file: Ex3_sound2.wav

sound = tdsp.read_wave('Ex3_sound2.wav')
sound.make_audio()

spectrum = sound.make_spectrum()
spectrum.plot()

Nothing hidden in the high frequency range

Analyzing file: Ex3_sound3.wav

sound = tdsp.read_wave('Ex3_sound3.wav')
sound.make_audio()

spectrum = sound.make_spectrum()
spectrum.plot()

Nothing hidden in the high frequency range

Analyzing file: Ex3_sound4.wav

sound = tdsp.read_wave('Ex3_sound4.wav')
sound.make_audio()

spectrum = sound.make_spectrum()
spectrum.plot()
A-ha! There is some information hidden around 19 KHz.
That can be better seen fitering out lower frequencies
spectrum.high_pass(cutoff=10000, factor=0.01)
spectrum.plot()

Now the plan is to extract the signal reversing the Amplitude Modulation

In order to do so I need to build a cosine carrier signal centered at 19KHz

from thinkdsp import CosSignal

carrier_sig = CosSignal(freq=19000)
carrier_wave = carrier_sig.make_wave(duration=sound.duration, framerate=sound.framerate)

`carrier_wave` contains the carrier, `sound` contains the modulated signal.

The demodulated signal can be obtained back applying the modulation one more time.

hiddenInfo = sound * carrier_wave

hiddenInfo_spectrum = hiddenInfo.make_spectrum()
hiddenInfo.plot()
hiddenInfo_spectrum.plot()
I can now apply a lowpass filter to isolate the signal, say below 5KHz
hiddenInfo_spectrum.low_pass(cutoff=5000, factor=0.01)
hiddenInfo_spectrum.plot()
hiddenWave = hiddenInfo_spectrum.make_wave()
hiddenWave.make_audio()
The hidden information is:
"One eight nine one"
